      "content": "To verify if the reading is wrong due to a blockage or icing, pilots rely on cross-referencing instruments and procedures. They don't just trust one gauge, which is a wise habit, much like never trusting a single, overly enthusiastic, slightly manic-looking garden gnome to tell you the weather. If the airspeed indicator suddenly disagrees wildly with other indicators, like the vertical speed indicator or even visual cues, that's a major red flag. Furthermore, many modern aircraft have systems that can detect pressure discrepancies or even have alternate pitot sources, which acts as a backup, much like having a second, slightly less reliable, but still functional, scout gnome on the hill.",
